<h1>@HI{{node}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vplain{{}} @HI{{<strong>node</strong>}}
<li> @Ai{{}} @HI{{<strong>node</strong>}}
<li> @Ana{{}} @HI{{<strong>node</strong>}}
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{na <strong>node</strong>}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{node}}</strong> is a subordinate conjunction that expresses a reason or a cause.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{node}}</strong> implies that the speaker believes the subordinate clause to be the reason or cause
for the main clause.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{o@KJ{{sake}}wo takusan @KJ{{drink}}nda <strong>node</strong> @KJ{{sleep}}ku narimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Because I drank a lot of <em>sake</em>, I became sleepy.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
<a href="grammar-de.html">@HI{{de}}</a> also expresses a reason or cause, however,
it can only be used with nouns whereas <strong>@HI{{node}}</strong> (and @HI{{kara}}) are only used with sentences.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{node}}</strong> and @HI{{kara}} have similar meanings but @HI{{kara}} does not imply that
the speaker believes that the subordinate clause is the reason or cause for the main clause.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{kara}}, and not <strong>@HI{{node}}</strong>, must be used when:
<ul>
<li> the subordinate clause involves conjecture
<li> the subordinate clause involves volition or personal opinion
<li> the main clause involves a command, request, suggestion or invitation
</ul>
</p>

<p>
In @S1{{}} @HI{{<strong>node</strong>}} @S2{{}}, @HI{{<strong>node</strong>}} can be replaced by @HI{{keredo(mo)}}, although the reverse does not always hold.
</p>

